# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: biathle
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:biathle/alexandre-dallenbach] He used to compete in swimming and triathlon before focusing on modern pentathlon.
[src:biathle/alexandre-dallenbach] He served a suspension for two years for doping in February 2012, following a positive finding for testosterone.
[src:biathle/alexandre-dallenbach] His results retroactively removed from July 12, 2011.
[src:biathle/alexandre-dallenbach] He run gold in the mixed relay and silver in the individual laser run at the 2023 World Modern Pentathlon Championships in Bath, England.
[src:biathle/alexandre-dallenbach] He competed at the 2024 Summer Olympics in Paris.
[src:biathle/alexandre-dallenbach] He qualified for the final with the best swimming time in his group.
[src:biathle/alexandre-dallenbach] Dällenbach was born on the island of Réunion.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] An **aquathlon** is a multisport race consisting of continuous run and swim elements.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] Competitors complete a swim immediately followed by a run over various distances.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] Athletes compete for fastest overall course completion, including the time transitioning between the disciplines.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] Aquathlon is one of a family of endurance based multisport races, which gained popularity from triathlon and various independent races in the second half of the twentieth century.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] Modern aquathlon is viewed as a discipline of triathlon as standard races cover the same distances as triathlon but without the cycling leg.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] As such the sport is governed by International Triathlon Union who organise the world championships each year.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] An earliest contested date for aquathlon is hard to state due to it being a combination of swimming and running which both have ancient origins.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] The modern roots of aquathlon can be traced to life guarding races in Australia, in the 1950s.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] Races would consist of a run along a beach, swim out to sea round a buoy and swim back to the beach, get out and then run back along the beach.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] By the 1960s the idea had spread to California in the United States, becoming popular with runners and swimmers.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] USA Triathlon argue that the first aquathlon event in the USA was the Dave Pain Birthday Biathlon, a race consisting of a run and swim first held in San Diego in 1971.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] This point is made due to aquathlons relation to triathlon and the fact that the Dave Pain Birthday Biathlon is the race that helped to inspire the first triathlon race (Mission Bay Triathlon) three years later.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] Aquathlon in general follows triathlon distances, but there is variability.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] Mostly open-water but there are some pool-based sprints/super-sprints.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] ITU "Warm water" standard distances are 2.5 km run, 1000m swim, 2.5 km run.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] If the rated water temperature is below 22 °C then it becomes a wetsuit-mandatory 1000m swim and a single 5 km run.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] "Long course" distances are 2000m swim and 10 km of running.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] Where the rated water temperature is low (around 16 °C) then the course may be shortened, and possibly cancelled.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] Different national federations have their own distances and temperature rules, typically related to the acclimatisation of national athletes.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] For example, the Icelanders will train/race at 10 °C whereas the BTF start at 12 °C.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] BTF aquathlons tend to be 750m wetsuit-mandatory/optional and a 5 km run.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] Aquathlons are most similar to triathlons, with the key difference being the lack of a cycle leg.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] The bike adds extra complexity for both the athletes and race organisers.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] Modern pentathlon is similar to an aquathlon in that both include swimming and running.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] But swimming and cross-country running are only two of the five events which make up the modern pentathlon, and these are held as distinct, noncontiguous events.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] Within the pentathlon sport, the term biathle is also used for (training) races comprising swimming and running.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] These however contain distance stemming from pentathlon races, for instance 200m swimming 3 km running.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] Another sport derived from triathlon is duathlon, which combines cycling and running but has omitted the swimming part.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] The ITU Aquathlon World Championships have been held annually since 1998.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] The Splash and Dash Youth Series, organized by USA Triathlon, is a popular variant of aquathlons designed for young athletes aged 7-15.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] These events combine swimming and running but do not require timing, emphasizing participation over competition.
[src:biathle/aquathlon] The series, which has over 50 events across the United States, offers a low-barrier entry into multisport activities for children, promoting fun and fitness without the need for extensive equipment.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Bali is the only Hindu-majority province in Indonesia, with 86.40% of the population adhering to Balinese Hinduism.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] It is renowned for its highly developed arts, including traditional and modern dance, sculpture, painting, leather, metalworking, and music.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The Indonesian International Film Festival is held every year in Bali.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Other international events that have been held in Bali include Miss World 2013, the 2018 Annual Meetings of the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank Group, and the 2022 G20 summit.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In March 2017, Tripadvisor named Bali as the world's top destination in its Traveler's Choice award, which it earned once again in January 2021 and 2026.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Bali is part of the Coral Triangle, an area with high diversity of marine species, mainly fish and turtles.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In this area alone, over 500 reef-building coral species can be found.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] For comparison, this is about seven times as many as in the entire Caribbean.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Bali is the home of the Subak irrigation system, a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] It is also home to a unified confederation of kingdoms composed of 10 traditional royal Balinese houses, each house ruling a specific geographic area.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The confederation is the successor of the Bali Kingdom.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The royal houses, which originated before Dutch colonisation, are not recognised by the government of Indonesia.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The name *Bali* is attested in ancient Balinese inscriptions as part of the compound *Vāli-dvīpa* (or *Wāli-dvīpa*), where Sanskrit *dvīpa* (Sanskrit: द्वीप) means "island".
[src:biathle/bali-p01] One of the earliest attestations of *Vāli-dvīpa* occurs in the Belanjong (Blanjong) pillar inscription, dated to Saka year 835 / Phalguna month, under King Sri Kesari Warmadewa (c.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The precise meaning of the element *Vāli* in *Vāli-dvīpa* is not certain.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Bali was inhabited around 2000 BC by Austronesian peoples who migrated originally from the island of Taiwan to Southeast Asia and Oceania through Maritime Southeast Asia.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Culturally and linguistically, the Balinese are closely related to the people of the Indonesian archipelago, Malaysia, Brunei, the Philippines, and Oceania.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Stone tools dating from this time have been found near the village of Cekik in the island's west.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In ancient Bali, nine Hindu sects existed: the Pasupata, Bhairawa, Siwa Shidanta, Vaishnava, Bodha, Brahma, Resi, Sora, and Ganapatya.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Each sect revered a specific deity as its personal Godhead.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Inscriptions from 896 and 911 do not mention a king until 914, when Sri Kesarivarma, a contemporary of the Kesari dynasty in the Kalinga Kingdom of ancient India, is mentioned.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] They also reveal an independent Bali, with a distinct dialect, being influenced by the Sanskrit and Pali languages, where Buddhism and Shaivism were practiced simultaneously.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Mpu Sindok's great-granddaughter, Mahendradatta (Gunapriyadharmapatni), married the Bali king Udayana Warmadewa (Dharmodayanavarmadeva) around 989, giving birth to Airlangga around 1001.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] This marriage also brought more Hinduism and Javanese culture to Bali.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Princess Sakalendukirana appeared in 1098.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Suradhipa reigned from 1115 to 1119, and Jayasakti from 1146 until 1150.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Jayapangus appears on inscriptions between 1178 and 1181, while Adikuntiketana and his son Paramesvara appear in 1204.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Balinese culture was strongly influenced by Indian, Chinese, and particularly Kalinga Hindu culture, beginning around the 1st century AD.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The name *Bali dwipa* ("Bali island") has been discovered from various inscriptions, including the Blanjong pillar inscription written by Sri Kesari Warmadewa in 914 AD, and mentioning **Walidwipa**.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] It was during this time that the people developed their complex irrigation system, *subak,* to grow rice in wet-field cultivation.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Some religious and cultural traditions still practiced today can be traced to this period.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The Hindu-Buddhist Majapahit Empire (1293–1520 AD) on eastern Java founded a Balinese colony in 1343.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The uncle of Hayam Wuruk is mentioned in the charters of 1384–86.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Mass Javanese immigration to Bali occurred in the next century when the Majapahit Empire fell in 1520.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Bali's government then became an independent collection of Hindu kingdoms, which led to a Balinese national identity and major enhancements in culture, arts, and economy.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The nation with various kingdoms became independent for up to 386 years until 1906, when the Dutch subjugated and repulsed the natives for economic control and took it over.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The first known European contact with Bali is thought to have been made in 1512, when a Portuguese expedition led by Antonio Abreu and Francisco Serrão sighted its northern shores.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] It was the first expedition of a series of bi-annual fleets to the Moluccas, which, throughout the 16th century, travelled along the coasts of the Sunda Islands.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Bali was also mapped in 1512, in the chart of Francisco Rodrigues, aboard the expedition.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In 1585, a ship foundered off the Bukit Peninsula and left a few Portuguese in the service of Dewa Agung.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In 1597, the Dutch merchant-explorer Cornelis de Houtman arrived at Bali, and the Dutch East India Company was established in 1602.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The Dutch government expanded its control across the Indonesian archipelago during the second half of the 19th century.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Dutch political and economic control over Bali began in the 1840s on the island's north coast when the Dutch pitted various competing Balinese realms against each other.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In the late 1890s, struggles between Balinese kingdoms on the island's south were exploited by the Dutch to increase their control.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In June 1860, the famous Welsh naturalist, Alfred Russel Wallace, travelled to Bali from Singapore, landing at Buleleng on the north coast of the island.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Wallace's trip to Bali was instrumental in helping him devise his Wallace Line theory.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The Wallace Line is a faunal boundary that runs through the strait between Bali and Lombok.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The Dutch mounted large naval and ground assaults at the Sanur region in 1906 and were met by the thousands of members of the royal family and their followers, who, rather than yield to the superior Dutch force, committed ritual suicide (*puputan*) to avoid the humiliation of surrender.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Despite Dutch demands for surrender, an estimated 200 Balinese killed themselves rather than surrender.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In the Dutch intervention in Bali, a similar mass suicide occurred in the face of a Dutch assault in Klungkung.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Afterward, the Dutch governors exercised administrative control over the island, but local control over religion and culture generally remained intact.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Dutch rule over Bali came later and was never as well established as in other parts of Indonesia, such as Java and Maluku.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In the 1930s, anthropologists Margaret Mead and Gregory Bateson, artists Miguel Covarrubias and Walter Spies, and musicologist Colin McPhee all spent time here.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Their accounts of the island and its peoples created a Western image of Bali as "an enchanted land of aesthetes at peace with themselves and nature".
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Soon after, Western tourists began to visit the island.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The film, which mostly consisted of scenes of topless Balinese women, was a great success in 1932, and was perhaps the main catalyst for the popularity of Bali among tourists.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The Dutch also dedicated significant efforts to implement *Baliseering* (lit.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] 'Balinization') politics to maintain traditions on the island, as well as preventing the Islamization of the Islamic sultanates from Java and banning Christian missionaries' activities.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Imperial Japan occupied Bali during World War II.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] It was not originally a target in their Netherlands East Indies Campaign; however, as the airfields on Borneo were inoperative due to heavy rains, the Imperial Japanese Army decided to occupy Bali, which did not suffer from comparable weather.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The island had no regular Royal Netherlands East Indies Army (KNIL) troops.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] There was only a Native Auxiliary Corps *Prajoda* (Korps Prajoda) consisting of about 600 native soldiers and several Dutch KNIL officers under the command of KNIL Lieutenant Colonel W.P.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] On 19 February 1942, the Japanese forces landed near the town of Sanoer (Sanur) and the island was quickly captured.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] During the Japanese occupation, a Balinese military officer, I Gusti Ngurah Rai, formed a Balinese 'freedom army'.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The harsh treatment of the Balinese by the Japanese occupation forces fomented more resentment than the former Dutch colonial rulers.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In 1945, Bali was liberated by the British 5th Infantry Division under the command of Major-General Robert Mansergh, who took the Japanese surrender.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Once Japanese forces had been repatriated, the island was handed over to the Dutch the following year.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In 1946, the Dutch constituted Bali as one of the 13 administrative districts of the newly proclaimed State of East Indonesia, a rival state to the Republic of Indonesia, which was proclaimed and headed by Sukarno and Hatta.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Bali was included in the "Republic of the United States of Indonesia" when the Netherlands recognised Indonesian independence on 29 December 1949.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The first governor of Bali, Anak Agung Bagus Suteja, was appointed by President Sukarno in 1958, when Bali became a province.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The 1963 eruption of Mount Agung killed thousands, created economic havoc, and forced many displaced Balinese to be transmigrated to other parts of Indonesia.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Mirroring the widening of social divisions across Indonesia in the 1950s and early 1960s, Bali saw conflict between supporters of the traditional caste system and those rejecting this system.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Politically, the opposition was represented by supporters of the Indonesian Communist Party (PKI) and the Indonesian Nationalist Party (PNI), with tensions and ill-feeling further increased by the PKI's land reform programmes.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] A purported coup attempt in Jakarta was averted by forces led by General Suharto.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The army became the dominant power as it instigated a violent anti-communist purge backed by Western powers, in which the army blamed the PKI for the coup.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Most estimates suggest that at least 500,000 people were killed across Indonesia, with an estimated 80,000 killed in Bali, equivalent to 5% of the island's population.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] With no Islamic forces involved as in Java and Sumatra, upper-caste PNI landlords led the extermination of PKI members.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] As a result of the 1965–66 massacres, Suharto was able to manoeuvre Sukarno out of the presidency.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] His "New Order" government re-established relations with Western countries.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The pre-war Bali, as "paradise," was revived in a modern form.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The resulting large growth in tourism has led to a dramatic increase in Balinese standards of living and significant foreign exchange earned for the country.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] A bombing in 2002 by militant Islamists in the tourist area of Kuta killed 202 people, mostly foreigners.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] This attack, and another in 2005, severely reduced tourism, producing much economic hardship on the island.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] On 9 July 2008, for the first time in Bali's history, the election for governor and vice governor of Bali was democratically elected by the people of Bali directly.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] On 27 November 2017, Mount Agung erupted five times, causing the evacuation of thousands, disrupting air travel, and causing much environmental damage.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Further eruptions also occurred between 2018 and 2019.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] On 15–16 November 2022, with the 2022 G20 Bali summit, the seventeenth meeting of the Group of Twenty (G20) was held in Nusa Dua.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The island of Bali lies 3.2 km (2.0 mi) east of Java, and is approximately 8 degrees south of the equator.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Bali and Java are separated by the Bali Strait.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Its population density was roughly 798 people/km2 (2,070 people/mi2) in mid 2024.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Bali's central mountains include several peaks over 2,000 metres (6,600 feet) in elevation and active volcanoes such as Mount Batur.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The highest is Mount Agung (3,031 m; 9,944 ft), known as the "mother mountain", which is an active volcano rated as one of the world's most likely sites for a massive eruption within the next 100 years.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In late 2017, Mount Agung started erupting and large numbers of people were evacuated, temporarily closing the island's airport.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Mountains range from centre to the eastern side, with Mount Agung the easternmost peak.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Bali's volcanic nature has contributed to its exceptional fertility, and its tall mountain ranges provide the high rainfall that supports the highly productive agricultural sector.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] South of the mountains is a broad, steadily descending area where most of Bali's large rice crop is grown.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The northern side of the mountains slopes more steeply to the sea and is the main coffee-producing area of the island, along with rice, vegetables, and cattle.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The longest river, Ayung River, flows approximately 75 km (47 mi) (see List of rivers of Bali).
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The island is surrounded by coral reefs.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Beaches in the south tend to have white sand, while those in the north and west have black sand.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Bali has no major waterways, although the Ho River is navigable by small *sampan* boats.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Black sand beaches between Pasut and Klatingdukuh are being developed for tourism, but apart from the seaside temple of Tanah Lot, they are not yet used for significant tourism.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The largest city is the provincial capital, Denpasar, near the southern coast.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Bali's second-largest city is the old colonial capital, Singaraja, which is located on the north coast and whose urban area is home to around 150,000 people in 2024.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Other important cities include the beach resort, Kuta, which is practically part of Denpasar's urban area, and Ubud, situated at the north of Denpasar, which is regarded as the island's cultural centre.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Three small islands lie to the immediate south-east and all are administratively part of the Klungkung regency of Bali: Nusa Penida, Nusa Lembongan and Nusa Ceningan.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] These islands are separated from Bali by the Badung Strait.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] To the east, the Lombok Strait separates Bali from Lombok and marks the biogeographical division between the fauna of the Indomalayan realm and the distinctly different fauna of Australasia.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The transition is known as the Wallace Line, named after Alfred Russel Wallace, who first proposed a transition zone between these two major biomes.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] When sea levels dropped during the Pleistocene ice age, Bali was connected to Java and Sumatra and to the mainland of Asia and shared the Asian fauna, but the deep water of the Lombok Strait continued to keep Lombok Island and the Lesser Sunda archipelago isolated.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Being just 8 degrees south of the equator, Bali has a fairly even climate all year round.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Average year-round temperature stands at around 30 °C (86 °F) with a humidity level of about 85%.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Daytime temperatures at low elevations vary between 20 and 33 °C (68 and 91 °F), but the temperatures decrease significantly with increasing elevation.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The west monsoon is in place from approximately October to April, and this can bring significant rain, particularly from December to March.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] During the rainy season, there are comparatively fewer tourists seen in Bali.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] During the Easter and Christmas holidays, the weather is very unpredictable.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Outside of the monsoon period, humidity is relatively low and any rain is unlikely in lowland areas.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Bali lies just to the west of the Wallace Line, and thus has a fauna that is Asian in character, with very little Australasian influence, and has more in common with Java than with Lombok.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] An exception is the yellow-crested cockatoo, a member of a primarily Australasian family.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] There are around 280 species of birds, including the critically endangered Bali myna, which is endemic.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Until the early 20th century, Bali was possibly home to several large mammals: banteng, leopard and the endemic Bali tiger.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The banteng still occurs in its domestic form, whereas leopards are found only in neighbouring Java, and the Bali tiger is extinct.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The last definite record of a tiger on Bali dates from 1937 when one was shot, though the subspecies may have survived until the 1940s or 1950s.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Pleistocene and Holocene megafaunas include banteng and giant tapir (based on speculations that they might have reached up to the Wallace Line), and rhinoceros.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Squirrels are quite commonly encountered, less often is the Asian palm civet, which is also kept in coffee farms to produce kopi luwak.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Bats are well represented, perhaps the most famous place to encounter them remaining is the Goa Lawah (Temple of the Bats) where they are worshipped by the locals and also constitute a tourist attraction.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] They also occur in other cave temples, for instance at Gangga Beach.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The crab-eating macaque, known locally as "kera", is quite common around human settlements and temples, where it becomes accustomed to being fed by humans, particularly in any of the three "monkey forest" temples, such as the popular one in the Ubud area.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] They are also quite often kept as pets by locals.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The second monkey, endemic to Java and some surrounding islands such as Bali, is far rarer and more elusive and is the Javan langur, locally known as "lutung".
[src:biathle/bali-p01] They occur in a few places apart from the West Bali National Park.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] They are born an orange colour, though they would have already changed to a more blackish colouration by their first year.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In Java, however, there is more of a tendency for this species to retain its juvenile orange colour into adulthood, and a mixture of black and orange monkeys can be seen together as a family.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Other rarer mammals include the Sunda leopard cat, Sunda pangolin and black giant squirrel.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Snakes include the king cobra and reticulated python.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The water monitor can grow to at least 1.5 m (4.9 ft) in length and 50 kg (110 lb) and can move quickly.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Dolphins are commonly encountered on the north coast near Singaraja and Lovina.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] A team of scientists surveyed from 29 April 2011, to 11 May 2011, at 33 sea sites around Bali.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] They discovered 952 species of reef fish of which 8 were new discoveries at Pemuteran, Gilimanuk, Nusa Dua, Tulamben and Candidasa, and 393 coral species, including two new ones at Padangbai and between Padangbai and Amed.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The average coverage level of healthy coral was 36% (better than in Raja Ampat and Halmahera by 29% or in Fakfak and Kaimana by 25%) with the highest coverage found in Gili Selang and Gili Mimpang in Candidasa, Karangasem Regency.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Among the larger trees the most common are: banyan trees, jackfruit, coconuts, bamboo species, acacia trees and also endless rows of coconuts and banana species.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Numerous flowers can be seen: hibiscus, frangipani, bougainvillea, poinsettia, oleander, jasmine, water lily, lotus, roses, begonias, orchids and hydrangeas exist.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] On higher grounds that receive more moisture, for instance, around Kintamani, certain species of fern trees, mushrooms and even pine trees thrive well.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Other plants with agricultural value include: salak, mangosteen, corn, Kintamani orange, coffee and water spinach.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Over-exploitation by the tourist industry has led to 200 out of 400 rivers on the island drying up.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Research suggests that the southern part of Bali would face a water shortage.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] To ease the shortage, the central government plans to build a water catchment and processing facility at Petanu River in Gianyar.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The 300 litres capacity of water per second will be channelled to Denpasar, Badung and Gianyar in 2013.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] A 2010 Environment Ministry report on its environmental quality index gave Bali a score of 99.65, which was the highest score of Indonesia's 33 provinces.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The score considers the level of total suspended solids, dissolved oxygen, and chemical oxygen demand in water.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Erosion at Lebih Beach has seen seven metres (23 feet) of land lost every year.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Decades ago, this beach was used for holy pilgrimages with more than 10,000 people, but they have now moved to Masceti Beach.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In 2017, a year when Bali received nearly 5.7 million tourists, government officials declared a "garbage emergency" in response to the covering of 3.6-mile stretch of coastline in plastic waste brought in by the tide, amid concerns that the pollution could dissuade visitors from returning.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Indonesia is one of the world's worst plastic polluters, with some estimates suggesting the country is the source of around 10 per cent of the world's plastic waste.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] On 3 February 2026, Bali launched a major beach clean up after President Prabowo Subianto's criticisms of the Bali's growing waste problem.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Hundreds of personnel from the Bali Police and the local military joined students and volunteers to collect rubbish from two of the island’s most popular tourist beaches: Kuta and Kedonganan in Badung Regency.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The governor is the highest officeholder in the Bali provincial government with the vice governor being the second highest officeholder.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The Governor of Bali is responsible for the territory of the Province of Bali.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The current governor in office in the province of Bali is I Wayan Koster who was first being elected in the 2018 Bali gubernatorial election accompanied by his first running mate at that time Tjokorda Oka Artha Ardana Sukawati (Cok Ace).
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Koster is the 8th governor of Bali, since the province was formed into the province of Bali in 1958 based on Law Number 64 of 1958.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Koster and Cok Ace were inaugurated by the president of the Republic of Indonesia at that time Joko Widodo, at the State Palace, Jakarta on September 5, 2018, for the five years term of office (2018–2023).
[src:biathle/bali-p01] After his term of office ended, Sang Made Mahendra Jaya was inaugurated as acting governor of Bali on September 5, 2023 with a limited authority in the government.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] After re-elected in 2024 I Wayan Koster and I Nyoman Giri Prasta was inaugurated on February 20, 2025 at the State Palace by the incumbent President of Indonesia Prabowo Subianto for the five years term of office (2025–2030).
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In the national legislature, Bali is represented by nine members, with a single electoral district covering the whole province.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The Bali Regional House of Representatives (DPRD), the provincial legislature, has 55 members.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The province's politics has historically been dominated by the Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle (PDI-P), which has won by far the most votes in every election in Bali since the first free elections in 1999, it currently forms the ruling government in the province.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] They are tabulated below with their areas and their populations at the 2010 census and the 2020 census, together with the official estimates as at mid 2024 and the Human Development Index for each regency and city.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The province forms one of Indonesia's 84 national electoral districts to elect members to the Indonesian parliament.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The **Bali Electoral District** consists of all of the 8 regencies in the province, together with the city of Denpasar, and elects 9 members to the People's Representative Council.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In the 1970s, the Balinese economy was largely agriculture-based in terms of both output and employment.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Tourism is now the largest single industry in terms of income, and as a result, Bali is one of Indonesia's wealthiest regions.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In 2003, around 80% of Bali's economy was tourism related.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] By the end of June 2011, the rate of non-performing loans of all banks in Bali were 2.23%, lower than the average of Indonesian banking industry non-performing loan rates (about 5%).
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The economy, however, suffered significantly as a result of the terrorist bombings in 2002 and 2005.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The tourism industry has since recovered from these events.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Although tourism produces the GDP's largest output, agriculture is still the island's biggest employer.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Fishing also provides a significant number of jobs.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Bali is also famous for its artisans who produce a vast array of handicrafts, including batik and ikat cloth and clothing, wooden carvings, stone carvings, painted art and silverware.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Notably, individual villages typically adopt a single product, such as wind chimes or wooden furniture.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The Arabica coffee production region is the highland region of Kintamani near Mount Batur.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Generally, Balinese coffee is processed using the wet method.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] This results in a sweet, soft coffee with good consistency.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Typical flavours include lemon and other citrus notes.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Many coffee farmers in Kintamani are members of a traditional farming system called Subak Abian, which is based on the Hindu philosophy of "Tri Hita Karana".
[src:biathle/bali-p01] According to this philosophy, the three causes of happiness are good relations with God, other people, and the environment.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The Subak Abian system is ideally suited to the production of fair trade and organic coffee production.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Arabica coffee from Kintamani is the first product in Indonesia to request a geographical indication.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In 2025, Bali received 6,948,754 international tourists, an increase of 9.72% compared to 2024..
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In 1963, the Bali Beach Hotel in Sanur was built by Sukarno and boosted tourism in Bali.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Before the Bali Beach Hotel construction, there were only three significant tourist-class hotels on the island.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Construction of hotels and restaurants began to spread throughout Bali.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Tourism further increased in Bali after the Ngurah Rai International Airport opened in 1970.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The Buleleng regency government encouraged the tourism sector as one of the mainstays for economic progress and social welfare.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The tourism industry is primarily focused in the south, while also significant in the other parts of the island.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The United States government lifted its travel warnings in 2008.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The Australian government issued an advisory on Friday, 4 May 2012, with the overall level of this advisory lowered to 'Exercise a high degree of caution'.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The Swedish government issued a new warning on Sunday, 10 June 2012, because of one tourist who died from methanol poisoning.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Australia last issued an advisory on Monday, 5 January 2015, due to new terrorist threats.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] An offshoot of tourism is the growing real estate industry.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Bali's real estate has been rapidly developing in the main tourist areas of Kuta, Legian, Seminyak, and Oberoi.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Most recently, high-end 5-star projects are under development on the Bukit peninsula, on the island's south side.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Expensive villas are being developed along the cliff sides of south Bali, with commanding panoramic ocean views.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Foreign and domestic, many Jakarta individuals and companies are fairly active, and investment into other areas of the island also continues to grow.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Land prices, despite the worldwide economic crisis, have remained stable.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In the last half of 2008, Indonesia's currency had dropped approximately 30% against the US dollar, providing many overseas visitors with improved value for their currencies.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Bali's tourism economy survived the terrorist bombings of 2002 and 2005, and the tourism industry has slowly recovered and surpassed its pre-terrorist bombing levels; the long-term trend has been a steady increase in visitor arrivals.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In 2010, Bali received 2.57 million foreign tourists, which surpassed the target of 2.0–2.3 million tourists.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The average occupancy of starred hotels achieved 65%, so the island still should be able to accommodate tourists for some years without any addition of new rooms/hotels, although at the peak season some of them are fully booked.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Bali received the Best Island award from Travel and Leisure in 2010.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Bali won because of its attractive surroundings (both mountain and coastal areas), diverse tourist attractions, excellent international and local restaurants, and the friendliness of the local people.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The Balinese culture and its religion are also considered the main factor of the award.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] One of the most prestigious events that symbolize a strong relationship between a god and its followers is Kecak dance.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] According to BBC Travel released in 2011, Bali is one of the World's Best Islands, ranking second after Santorini, Greece.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In 2006, Elizabeth Gilbert's memoir *Eat, Pray, Love* was published, and in August 2010 it was adapted into the film *Eat Pray Love*.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] It took place at Ubud and Padang-Padang Beach in Bali.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Both the book and the film fuelled a boom in tourism in Ubud, the hill town and cultural and tourist centre that was the focus of Gilbert's quest for balance and love through traditional spirituality and healing.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In January 2016, after musician David Bowie died, it was revealed that in his will, Bowie asked for his ashes to be scattered in Bali, conforming to Buddhist rituals.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] He had visited and performed in several Southeast Asian cities early in his career, including Bangkok and Singapore.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Since 2011, China has displaced Japan as the second-largest supplier of tourists to Bali, while Australia still tops the list while India has also emerged as a greater supplier of tourists.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Chinese tourists increased by 17% in 2011 from 2010 due to the impact of ACFTA and new direct flights to Bali.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In January 2012, Chinese tourists increased by 222.18% compared to January 2011, while Japanese tourists declined by 23.54% year on year.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Bali is a very popular tourist destination for Indians.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Bali authorities reported the island had 2.88 million foreign tourists and 5 million domestic tourists in 2012, marginally surpassing the expectations of 2.8 million foreign tourists.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Based on a Bank Indonesia survey in May 2013, 34.39 per cent of tourists are upper-middle class, spending between $1,286 and $5,592, and are dominated by Australia, India, France, China, Germany and the UK.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Some Chinese tourists have increased their levels of spending from previous years.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] 30.26 per cent of tourists are middle class, spending between $662 and $1,285.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In 2017 it was expected that Chinese tourists would outnumber Australian tourists.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In January 2020, 10,000 Chinese tourists cancelled trips to Bali due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Because of the COVID-19 pandemic travel restrictions, Bali welcomed 1.07 million international travelers in 2020, most of them between January and March, which is −87% compared to 2019.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In the first half of 2021, they welcomed 43 international travelers.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The pandemic presented a major blow on Bali's tourism-dependent economy.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] On 3 February 2022, Bali reopened again for the first foreign tourists after 2 years of being closed due to the pandemic.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In 2022 Indonesia's Minister of Health, Budi Sadikin, stated that the tourism industry in Bali will be complemented by the medical industry.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] At the beginning of 2023, the governor of Bali demanded a ban on the use of motorcycles by tourists.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] This happened after a series of accidents.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Wayan Koster proposed to cancel the violators' visas.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The move sparked widespread outrage on social media.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The Ngurah Rai International Airport is located near Jimbaran, on the isthmus at the southernmost part of the island.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] A coastal road circles the island, and three major two-lane arteries cross the central mountains at passes reaching 1,750 m in height (at Penelokan).
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The Ngurah Rai Bypass is a four-lane expressway that partly encircles Denpasar.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] There is a car ferry between Gilimanuk on the west coast of Bali to Ketapang on Java which started running in the 1930s.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Two bus systems exist: Trans Sarbagita and Trans Metro Dewata.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In December 2010 the Government of Indonesia invited investors to build a new Tanah Ampo Cruise Terminal at Karangasem, Bali with a projected worth of $30 million.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] On 17 July 2011, the first cruise ship (Sun Princess) anchored about 400 metres (1,300 feet) away from the wharf of Tanah Ampo harbour.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The current pier is only 154 metres (505 feet) but will eventually be extended to 300 to 350 metres (980–1,150 feet) to accommodate international cruise ships.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The harbour is safer than the existing facility at Benoa and has a scenic backdrop of east Bali mountains and green rice fields.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The tender for improvement was subject to delays, and as of July 2013 the situation was unclear with cruise line operators complaining and even refusing to use the existing facility at Tanah Ampo.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] A memorandum of understanding was signed by two ministers, Bali's governor and Indonesian Train Company to build 565 kilometres (351 miles) of railway along the coast around the island.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] As of July 2015, no details of these proposed railways have been released.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In 2019 it was reported in *Gapura Bali* that Wayan Koster, governor of Bali, "is keen to improve Bali's transportation infrastructure and is considering plans to build an electric rail network across the island".
[src:biathle/bali-p01] On 16 March 2011 (Tanjung) Benoa port received the "Best Port Welcome 2010" award from London's "Dream World Cruise Destination" magazine.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] Government plans to expand the role of Benoa port as export-import port to boost Bali's trade and industry sector.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In 2013, The Tourism and Creative Economy Ministry advised that 306 cruise liners were scheduled to visit Indonesia, an increase of 43 per cent compared to the previous year.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] In May 2011, an integrated Area Traffic Control System (ATCS) was implemented to reduce traffic jams at four crossing points: Ngurah Rai statue, Dewa Ruci Kuta crossing, Jimbaran crossing and Sanur crossing.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] ATCS is an integrated system connecting all traffic lights, CCTVs and other traffic signals with a monitoring office at the police headquarters.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] It has successfully been implemented in other ASEAN countries and will be implemented at other crossings in Bali.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] On 21 December 2011, construction started on the Nusa Dua-Benoa-Ngurah Rai International Airport toll road, which will also provide a special lane for motorcycles.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] This has been done by seven state-owned enterprises led by PT Jasa Marga with 60% of the shares.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] PT Jasa Marga Bali Tol will construct the 9.91-kilometre-long (6.16-mile) toll road (totally 12.7 kilometres (7.89 miles) with access road).
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The construction is estimated to cost Rp.2.49 trillion ($273.9 million).
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The project goes through 2 kilometres (1 mile) of mangrove forest and through 2.3 kilometres (1.4 miles) of beach, both within 5.4 hectares (13 acres) area.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] The elevated toll road is built over the mangrove forest on 18,000 concrete pillars that occupied two hectares of mangrove forest.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] This was compensated by the planting of 300,000 mangrove trees along the road.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] On 21 December 2011, the Dewa Ruci 450-metre (1,480-foot) underpass has also started on the busy Dewa Ruci junction near Bali Kuta Galeria with an estimated cost of Rp136 billion ($14.9 million) from the state budget.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] On 23 September 2013, the Bali Mandara Toll Road was opened, with the Dewa Ruci Junction underpass being opened previously.
[src:biathle/bali-p01] To solve chronic traffic problems, the province will also build a toll road connecting Serangan with Tohpati, a toll road connecting Kuta, Denpasar, and Tohpati, and a flyover connecting Kuta and Ngurah Rai Airport.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] In 2021, the Indonesian Ministry of Tourism estimated that there were 109,801 foreigners living on Bali, with most originating from Russia, United States, Australia, United Kingdom, Germany, Japan, France, Italy, India, and the Netherlands.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] A DNA study in 2005 by Karafet et al., found that 84% of Balinese Y-chromosomes are of likely Austronesian origin, 12% of likely Indian origin and 2% of likely Melanesian origin.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] According to a recent genetic study, the Balinese, together with the Javanese and Sundanese, have a significant admixture of Austroasiatic and Austronesian ancestries.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] The majority of the population inhabiting the province of Bali are the local ethnic, namely the Balinese and indigenous Bali Aga people.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] The Balinese have a cultural richness that is known worldwide, so that Bali is the main destination for foreign tourists to Indonesia.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] In addition to the rich beaches, the culture that is of interest in Bali is its dances, such as the Kecak dance, festivals such as Ogoh-ogoh, and others.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] The largest ethnic group outside the Balinese people is the Javanese people.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Pre-modern Bali had four castes, but with a "very strong tradition of communal decision-making and interdependence".
[src:biathle/bali-p02] The four castes have been classified as Sudra (Shudra), Wesia (Vaishyas), Satria (Kshatriyas) and Brahmana (Brahmin).
[src:biathle/bali-p02] In Bali, the Shudra (locally spelt *Soedra*) has typically been the temple priests, though depending on the demographics, a temple priest may also be from the other three castes.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] In most regions, it has been the Shudra who typically make offerings to the gods on behalf of the Hindu devotees, chant prayers, recite *meweda* (Vedas), and set the course of Balinese temple festivals.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] About 86.40% of Bali's population adheres to Balinese Hinduism, formed as a combination of existing local beliefs and Hindu beliefs from mainland Southeast Asia and South Asia.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] The Balinese people and Bali Aga are generally Hindu with some being Muslim (3.24%) and Christian (1.26%).
[src:biathle/bali-p02] The Javanese, Sundanese, Sasak, and Malay people are generally Muslim and some are also Hindu or Christian.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Meanwhile, people from East Nusa Tenggara, as well as people of the Papua, Batak, Chinese and some other Indonesian ethnic groups that aren't traditionally Muslim are generally Christian, with small minority are Hindu and Muslim.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] The village of Blimbing Sari in the Melaya district of Jembrana Regency, not far from Gilimanuk Port, is Christian, and the residents there are native Balinese, but the church is shaped like a Hindu temple.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] The general beliefs and practices of *Agama Hindu Dharma* mix ancient traditions and contemporary pressures placed by Indonesian laws that permit only monotheist belief under the national ideology of *Pancasila*.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Traditionally, Hinduism in Indonesia had a pantheon of deities and that tradition of belief continues in practice; further, Hinduism in Indonesia granted freedom and flexibility to Hindus as to when, how and where to pray.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] However, officially, the Indonesian government considers and advertises Indonesian Hinduism as a monotheistic religion with certain officially recognised beliefs that comply with its national ideology.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Indonesian school textbooks describe Hinduism as having one supreme being, Hindus offering three daily mandatory prayers, and Hinduism as having certain common beliefs that in part parallel those of Islam.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Some scholars contest whether these Indonesian government recognised and assigned beliefs to reflect the traditional beliefs and practices of Hindus in Indonesia before Indonesia gained independence from Dutch colonial rule.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Balinese Hinduism has roots in Indian Hinduism and Buddhism, which arrived through Java.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Hindu influences reached the Indonesian Archipelago as early as the first century.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Historical evidence is unclear about the diffusion process of cultural and spiritual ideas from India.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Java legends refer to Saka-era, traced to 78 AD.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Stories from the Mahabharata Epic have been traced in Indonesian islands to the 1st century; however, the versions mirror those found in the southeast Indian peninsular region (now Tamil Nadu and southern Karnataka and Andhra Pradesh).
[src:biathle/bali-p02] The Bali tradition adopted the pre-existing animistic traditions of the indigenous people.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] This influence strengthened the belief that the gods and goddesses are present in all things.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Every element of nature, therefore, possesses its power, which reflects the power of the gods.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] A rock, tree, dagger, or woven cloth is a potential home for spirits whose energy can be directed for good or evil.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Balinese Hinduism is deeply interwoven with art and ritual.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Ritualising states of self-control are a notable feature of religious expression among the people, who for this reason have become famous for their graceful and decorous behavior.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Apart from the majority of Balinese Hindus, there also exist Chinese immigrants whose traditions have melded with that of the locals.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] As a result, these Sino-Balinese embrace their original religion, which is a mixture of Buddhism, Christianity, Taoism, and Confucianism, and find a way to harmonise it with the local traditions.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Hence, it is not uncommon to find local Sino-Balinese during the local temple's *odalan*.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Moreover, Balinese Hindu priests are invited to perform rites alongside a Chinese priest in the event of the death of a Sino-Balinese.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Nevertheless, the Sino-Balinese claim to embrace Buddhism for administrative purposes, such as their Identity Cards.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] The Roman Catholic community has a diocese, the Diocese of Denpasar that encompasses the province of Bali and West Nusa Tenggara and has its cathedral located in Denpasar.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Balinese and Indonesian are the most widely spoken languages in Bali, and the vast majority of Balinese people are bilingual or trilingual.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] The most common spoken language around the tourist areas is Indonesian, as many people in the tourist sector are not solely Balinese, but migrants from Java, Lombok, Sumatra, and other parts of Indonesia.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] The Balinese language is heavily stratified due to the Balinese caste system.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Kawi and Sanskrit are also commonly used by some Hindu priests in Bali, as Hindu literature was mostly written in Sanskrit.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] English and Chinese are the next most common languages (and the primary foreign languages) of many Balinese, owing to the requirements of the tourism industry, as well as the English-speaking community and huge Chinese-Indonesian population.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Other foreign languages, such as Japanese, Korean, French, Russian or German, are often used in multilingual signs for foreign tourists.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Bali is renowned for its diverse and sophisticated art forms, such as painting, sculpture, woodcarving, handcrafts, and performing arts.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Balinese cuisine is also distinctive, and unlike the rest of Indonesia, pork is commonly found in Balinese dishes such as Babi Guling.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Balinese percussion orchestra music, known as *gamelan*, is highly developed and varied.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Balinese performing arts often portray stories from Hindu epics such as the Ramayana but with heavy Balinese influence.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Famous Balinese dances include *pendet*, *legong*, *baris*, *topeng*, *barong*, *gong kebyar*, and *kecak* (the monkey dance).
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Bali boasts one of the most diverse and innovative performing arts cultures in the world, with paid performances at thousands of temple festivals, private ceremonies, and public shows.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] In 2018 Governor I Wayan Koster issued Bali Governor's Regulation No.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] 79 of 2018 which mandated that city officials wear traditional Balinese dress, such as that made of *songket*.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] 4 of 2021 which specified the use of Endek fabrics, and was expanded to high-ranking individuals in the private sector and other institutions.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Most temples have an inner courtyard and an outer courtyard which are arranged with the inner courtyard furthest *kaja*.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] These spaces serve as performance venues since most Balinese rituals are accompanied by any combination of music, dance, and drama.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] The performances that take place in the inner courtyard are classified as *wali*, the most sacred rituals which are offerings exclusively for the gods, while the outer courtyard is where *bebali* ceremonies are held, which are intended for gods and people.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Lastly, performances meant solely for the entertainment of humans take place outside the temple's walls and are called *bali-balihan*.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] This three-tiered system of classification was standardised in 1971 by a committee of Balinese officials and artists to better protect the sanctity of the oldest and most sacred Balinese rituals from being performed for a paying audience.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Tourism, Bali's chief industry, has provided the island with a foreign audience that is eager to pay for entertainment, thus creating new performance opportunities and more demand for performers.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] The impact of tourism is controversial since before it became integrated into the economy, the Balinese performing arts did not exist as a capitalist venture, and were not performed for entertainment outside of their respective ritual context.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Since the 1930s sacred rituals such as the *barong* dance have been performed both in their original contexts, as well as exclusively for paying tourists.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] This has led to new versions of many of these performances that have developed according to the preferences of foreign audiences; some villages have a *barong* mask specifically for non-ritual performances and an older mask that is only used for sacred performances.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Throughout the year, there are many festivals celebrated locally or island-wide according to the traditional calendars.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] The Hindu New Year, *Nyepi*, is celebrated in the spring by a day of silence.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] On this day everyone stays at home and tourists are encouraged (or required) to remain in their hotels.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] On the day before New Year, large and colourful sculptures of *Ogoh-ogoh* monsters are paraded and burned in the evening to drive away evil spirits.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Other festivals throughout the year are specified by the Balinese *pawukon* calendrical system.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Celebrations are held for many occasions such as a tooth-filing (coming-of-age ritual), cremation or *odalan* (temple festival).
[src:biathle/bali-p02] One of the most important concepts that Balinese ceremonies have in common is that of *désa kala patra*, which refers to how ritual performances must be appropriate in both the specific and general social context.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Many ceremonial art forms such as *wayang kulit* and *topeng* are highly improvisatory, providing flexibility for the performer to adapt the performance to the current situation.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Many celebrations call for a loud, boisterous atmosphere with much activity, and the resulting aesthetic, *ramé*, is distinctively Balinese.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Often two or more *gamelan* ensembles will be performing well within earshot, and sometimes compete with each other to be heard.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Likewise, the audience members talk amongst themselves, get up and walk around, or even cheer on the performance, which adds to the many layers of activity and the liveliness typical of *ramé*.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Balinese society continues to revolve around each family's ancestral village, to which the cycle of life and religion is closely tied.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Coercive aspects of traditional society, such as customary law sanctions imposed by traditional authorities such as village councils (including "kasepekang", or shunning) have risen in importance as a consequence of the democratisation and decentralisation of Indonesia since 1998.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Other than Balinese sacred rituals and festivals, the government presents Bali Arts Festival to showcase Bali's performing arts and various artworks produced by the local talents that they have.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] It is held once a year, from the second week of June until the end of July.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Southeast Asia's biggest annual festival of words and ideas Ubud Writers and Readers Festival is held at Ubud in October, which is participated by the world's most celebrated writers, artists, thinkers, and performers.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] One unusual tradition is the naming of children in Bali.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] In general, Balinese people name their children depending on the order they are born, and the names are the same for both males and females.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Bali was the host of Miss World 2013 (63rd edition of the Miss World pageant).
[src:biathle/bali-p02] It was the first time Indonesia hosted an international beauty pageant.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] In 2022, Bali also co-hosted Miss Grand International 2022 along with Jakarta, West Java, and Banten.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Bali has hosted several milestone regional and sectoral gatherings, including foundational ASEAN summits.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Key agreements signed on the island include the 1976 Declaration of ASEAN Concord and the Treaty of Amity and Cooperation in Southeast Asia, as well as the Bali Concord II (2003) and Bali Concord III (2011).
[src:biathle/bali-p02] It also serves as the venue for the East Asia Summit's "Bali Principles" for mutually beneficial relations.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] The province has been a focal point for global environmental and trade governance.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] It hosted the 2007 UNFCCC COP13, which produced the Bali Road Map, and the 2013 APEC Leaders' Week.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Additionally, the WTO Ninth Ministerial Conference adopted the "Bali Package" on trade facilitation in 2013.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Bali also anchors regional governance architectures through recurring platforms like the Bali Process on people smuggling and the Bali Democracy Forum.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] In 2022, the UN’s Global Platform for Disaster Risk Reduction was held on the island.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] More recently, Bali has hosted the Multilateral Naval Exercise Komodo (MNEK).
[src:biathle/bali-p02] The 2025 iteration involved 38 countries and 19 foreign warships at Tanjung Benoa.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] These drills occurred amid regional tensions in the South China Sea regarding maritime claims, including China's "nine-dash line" which a 2016 arbitral tribunal under UNCLOS found had no legal basis.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Bali is a major world surfing destination with popular breaks dotted across the southern coastline and around the offshore island of Nusa Lembongan.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] As part of the Coral Triangle, Bali, including Nusa Penida, offers a wide range of dive sites with varying types of reefs, and tropical aquatic life.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Bali was the host of 2008 Asian Beach Games.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] It was the second time Indonesia hosted an Asia-level multi-sport event, after Jakarta held the 1962 Asian Games.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] In 2023, Bali was the location for a major eSports event, the Dota 2 Bali Major, the third and final Major of the Dota Pro Circuit season.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] The event was held at the Ayana Estate and the Champa Garden, and it was the first time that a Dota Pro Circuit Major was held in Indonesia.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] In football, Bali is home to Bali United football club, which plays in Liga 1.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] The team was relocated from Samarinda, East Kalimantan to Gianyar, Bali.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Harbiansyah Hanafiah, the main commissioner of Bali United explained that he changed the name and moved the home base because there was no representative from Bali in the highest football tier in Indonesia.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] Another reason was due to local fans in Samarinda preferring to support Pusamania Borneo F.C. rather than Persisam.
[src:biathle/bali-p02] In June 2012, Subak, the irrigation system for paddy fields in Jatiluwih, central Bali was listed as a Natural UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:biathle/batumi] Batumi is located on the site of the ancient Greek colony in Colchis called "*Bathus"* or "*Bathys"*, derived from (Ancient Greek: βαθύς λιμεν, *bathus limen*; or βαθύς λιμήν, *bathys limēn*; lit. the 'deep harbor').
[src:biathle/batumi] 117–138 AD), it was converted into a fortified Roman port and later deserted for the fortress of Petra founded in the time of Justinian I (c.
[src:biathle/batumi] Garrisoned by the Roman-Byzantine forces, it was formally a possession of the kingdom of Lazica until being occupied briefly by the Arabs, who did not hold it; In 780 Lazica fell to kingdom of Abkhazia via a dynastic union; the latter led the unification of the Georgian monarchy in the 11th century.
[src:biathle/batumi] From 1010, it was governed by the *eristavi* (ერისთავი, viceroy) of the king of Georgia.
[src:biathle/batumi] In the late 15th century, after the disintegration of the Georgian kingdom, Batumi passed to the princes (*mtavari*, მთავარი) of Guria, a western Georgian principality under the sovereignty of the kings of Imereti.
[src:biathle/batumi] De Thoisy was taken captive and released through the mediation of the emperor John IV of Trebizond.
[src:biathle/batumi] In the 15th century in the reign of the prince Kakhaber Gurieli, the Ottomans conquered the town and its district but did not hold them.
[src:biathle/batumi] They returned to it in force a century later and inflicted a decisive defeat on the Georgian armies at Sokhoista.
[src:biathle/batumi] Batumi was recaptured by the Georgians several times, first in 1546 by prince Rostom Gurieli, who lost it soon afterwards, and again in 1609 by Mamia II Gurieli.
[src:biathle/batumi] In 1703, Batumi again became part of the Ottoman Empire.
[src:biathle/batumi] In the one-and-a-half century of Ottoman rule it grew into a provincial port serving the Empire's hinterlands on the eastern fringes of the Black Sea.
[src:biathle/batumi] After the Ottoman conquest, Islamization of the hitherto Christian region began but this was terminated and to a great degree reversed, after the area was annexed to Russian Imperial Georgia after the Russo-Turkish War of 1877–78.
[src:biathle/batumi] It was the last Black Sea port annexed by Russia during the Russian conquest of that area of the Caucasus.
[src:biathle/batumi] In 1878, Batumi was annexed by the Russian Empire in accordance with the Treaty of San Stefano between Russia and the Ottoman Empire (ratified on 23 March).
[src:biathle/batumi] Occupied by the Russians on 28 August 1878, the town was declared a free port until 1886.
[src:biathle/batumi] It functioned as the center of a special military district until being incorporated in the Kutaisi Governorate on 12 June 1883.
[src:biathle/batumi] Finally, on 1 June 1903, with the Artvin Okrug, the Batum Okrug was established as the Batum Oblast and placed under the direct administration of the Viceroy of the Caucasus.
[src:biathle/batumi] The expansion of Batumi began with the construction of the Batumi–Tiflis–Baku Transcaucasus Railway (completed in 1883), and the Baku–Batumi pipeline which opened in 1907.
[src:biathle/batumi] Henceforth, Batumi became the chief Russian oil port in the Black Sea.
[src:biathle/batumi] The population increased rapidly doubling within 20 years: from 8,671 inhabitants in 1882 to 12,000 in 1889.
[src:biathle/batumi] By 1902 the population had reached 16,000, with 1,000 working in the refinery for Baron Rothschild's Caspian and Black Sea Oil Company.
[src:biathle/batumi] In the late 1880s and after, more than 7,400 Doukhobor emigrants sailed for Canada from Batumi, after the government agreed to let them emigrate.
[src:biathle/batumi] Quakers and Tolstoyans aided in collecting funds for the relocation of the religious minority, which had come into conflict with the Imperial government over its refusal to serve in the military and other positions.
[src:biathle/batumi] Canada settled them in Manitoba and Saskatchewan.
[src:biathle/batumi] During 1901, sixteen years prior to the October Revolution, Joseph Stalin, the future leader of the Soviet Union, lived in the city organizing strikes.
[src:biathle/batumi] On 3 March 1918, the Treaty of Brest-Litovsk gave the city back to the Ottoman Empire, confirmed in the Treaty of Batum of June 1918 between the Ottoman Empire and the new Democratic Republic of Georgia.
[src:biathle/batumi] As result of the end of World War I the British took control over Batumi from December 1918, who stayed until July 1920 when the city and province was transferred to the Democratic Republic of Georgia, which gave Adjara autonomy.
[src:biathle/batumi] In 1921 Kemal Atatürk ceded the northern part of Adjara, including Batumi, to the Bolsheviks who reconquered the Transcaucasian republics, on the condition that it be granted autonomy for the sake of the Muslims among Batumi's mixed population.
[src:biathle/batumi] When Georgia regained its independence from the Soviet Union in 1991, Aslan Abashidze was appointed head of Adjara's governing council and subsequently held onto power throughout the unrest of the 1990s.
[src:biathle/batumi] While Abkhazia and South Ossetia areas attempted to break away from the Georgian state, Adjara remained an integral part of the republic.
[src:biathle/batumi] Instead, Abashidze turned Adjara into his personal fiefdom.
[src:biathle/batumi] In May 2004, he fled to Russia after mass protests in Batumi, which concluded the 2004 Adjara crisis.
[src:biathle/batumi] Batumi today is one of the main port cities of Georgia.
[src:biathle/batumi] It has the capacity for 80,000-ton tankers to take materials such as oil that are shipped through Georgia from Central Asia.
[src:biathle/batumi] Additionally, the city exports regional agricultural products.
[src:biathle/batumi] Since 1995 the freight conversion of the port has constantly risen, with an approximate 8 million tons in 2001.
[src:biathle/batumi] The annual revenue from the port is estimated at between $200 million and $300 million.
[src:biathle/batumi] Since the change of power in Adjara, Batumi has attracted international investors, and the prices of real estate in the city have trebled since 2001.
[src:biathle/batumi] In July 2007, the seat of the Constitutional Court of Georgia was moved from Tbilisi to Batumi to stimulate regional development.
[src:biathle/batumi] Several new hotels opened after 2009, first the Sheraton in 2010 and the Radisson Blu in 2011.
[src:biathle/batumi] The city features several casinos that attract tourists from Turkey, where gambling is illegal.
[src:biathle/batumi] Batumi was host to the Russian 12th Military Base.
[src:biathle/batumi] Following the Rose Revolution, the central government pushed for the removal of these forces and reached an agreement in 2005 with Moscow.
[src:biathle/batumi] According to the agreement, the process of withdrawal was planned to be completed in 2008, but the Russians completed the transfer of the Batumi base to Georgia on 13 November 2007, ahead of schedule.
[src:biathle/batumi] Batumi has a humid subtropical climate (*Cfa*) according to Köppen's classification.
[src:biathle/batumi] The city's climate is heavily influenced by the onshore flow from the Black Sea and is subject to the orographic effect of the nearby hills and mountains, resulting in significant rainfall throughout most of the year, making Batumi the wettest city in both Georgia and the entire Caucasus Region.
[src:biathle/batumi] The average annual temperature in Batumi is approximately 14 °C (57 °F).
[src:biathle/batumi] January is the coldest month with an average temperature of 5 °C (41 °F).
[src:biathle/batumi] August is the hottest month, with an average temperature of 22 °C (72 °F).
[src:biathle/batumi] The absolute minimum recorded temperature is −6 °C (21 °F), and the absolute maximum is 40 °C (104 °F).
[src:biathle/batumi] The number of days with daily temperatures above 10 °C (50 °F) is 239.
[src:biathle/batumi] The city receives 1958 hours of sunshine per year.
[src:biathle/batumi] Batumi's average annual precipitation is 2,435 mm (95.9 in).
[src:biathle/batumi] November is the wettest month with an average of 312 mm (12.3 in) of precipitation, while May is the driest, averaging 84 mm (3.3 in).
[src:biathle/batumi] Batumi receives snow most years, but it is often limited in amount (accumulating snowfall of more than 30 cm (11.8 in) is rare), and the number of days with snow cover for the year is 12.
[src:biathle/batumi] The average level of relative humidity ranges from 70 to 80%.
[src:biathle/batumi] A large Kempinski hotel and casino is to open in 2013, a Hilton Hotel as well as a 47-storey Trump Tower is also planned.
[src:biathle/batumi] Alliance Privilege, a building compromising Marriott Hotel, Casino and serviced apartments is one of the contemporary buildings with unique architecture by the beach.
[src:biathle/batumi] Of the 4,970 inhabitants in 1872, about 4,500 were Muslim (Adjarians, Turks, Circassians, and Abkhazians).
[src:biathle/batumi] In the 1897 census, the Orthodox Christian population was 15,495 (mostly Slavs) while Muslims numbered 3,156, including some of whom were citizens of Turkey.
[src:biathle/batumi] As of 2014, out of 152,839 inhabitants of Batumi, 68,7% is Eastern Orthodox Christian, and they primarily adhere to the national Georgian Orthodox Church.
[src:biathle/batumi] Muslims make up 25,3% of population, while there are also Catholic, Armenian Apostolic, Jehovah's Witness, Seventh-day Adventist, and Jewish communities.
[src:biathle/batumi] Batumi has 18 various museums, including State Art Museum of Adjara.
[src:biathle/batumi] Rugby Union club Batumi RC competes in the Georgian Didi 10 and previously competed in the Pan-European Rugby Europe Super Cup.
[src:biathle/batumi] Football club FC Dinamo Batumi play at the Batumi stadium.
[src:biathle/batumi] A sculpture by Tamara Kvesitadze of two standing figures on the seashore shows the story first told in the 1937 Austrian novel, Ali and Nino, of lovers who are parted after World War I.
[src:biathle/batumi] Each day, the two figures move toward each other but never stay together.
[src:biathle/batumi] Ali, an Azerbaijani Muslim, falls in love with Georgian princess, Nino, but sadly, after they are finally able to get together, the war hits home and Ali is killed.
[src:biathle/batumi] The city is served by Batumi Airport, one of three international airports in the country.
[src:biathle/batumi] The main types of public transport are buses, minibusses, and taxis.
[src:biathle/batumi] Using the service is possible by *BATUMICARD*, transit card, or debit/credit cards.
[src:biathle/batumi] Buses connect almost everywhere in the city.
[src:biathle/batumi] A bike-sharing system named *BatumVelo* allows you to rent a bicycle on the street with a smart card.
[src:biathle/batumi] The port of Batumi is on one of the routes of China's proposed Eurasian Land Bridge (part of the "New Silk Road"), which would see an eastern freight link to China via Azerbaijan and the Caspian Sea, and a western link by ferry to Ukraine and on to Europe.
[src:biathle/batumi] Batumi has become an emerging centre for medical education in the Caucasus region, attracting international students due to its affordable tuition and English-language programs.
[src:biathle/batumi] Institutions such as **Batumi Shota Rustaveli State University**, BAU International University offer accredited medical degrees recognized across America, Europe and Asia.
[src:biathle/batumi] The city’s growth in medical education is supported by modern infrastructure and increasing foreign enrollment.
[src:biathle/batumi] According to *The Times of India*, many Indian students choose Batumi for MBBS studies due to simplified admission processes and NMC-recognized curriculum.
[src:biathle/biathle-world-championships] Biathle is a world class sport but not an Olympic one.
[src:biathle/biathle-world-championships] Competitions are held under rules of the Union Internationale de Pentathlon Moderne (UIPM).
[src:biathle/biathle-world-championships] The Biathle World Championships have been held in September or October annually since 1999.
[src:biathle/biathle-world-championships] The first event was held in Monaco, and returned there every two years between 2003 and 2009.
[src:biathle/biathle-world-championships] Approximately 500 athletes have competed at each edition of the championships, representing some 50 countries.
[src:biathle/biathlon] Norwegian skiing regiments organized military skiing contests in the 18th century, divided into four classes: shooting at mark while skiing at top speed, downhill race among trees, downhill race on big hills without falling, and a long race on flat ground while carrying a rifle and military pack.
[src:biathle/biathlon] In modern terminology, these military contests included downhill, slalom, biathlon, and cross-country skiing.
[src:biathle/biathlon] One of the world's first known ski clubs, *Trysil Skytte- og Skiløberforening* (the Trysil Rifle and Ski Club), was formed in Norway in 1861 to promote national defense at the local level.
[src:biathle/biathlon] 20th century variants include *Forsvarsrennet* (the military contest), a 17 km cross-country race with shooting, and the military cross-country race at 30 km including marksmanship.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The modern biathlon is a civilian variant of the old military combined exercise.
[src:biathle/biathlon] In Norway, the biathlon was, until 1984, a branch of *Det frivillige Skyttervesen*, an organization set up by the government to promote civilian marksmanship in support of national defence.
[src:biathle/biathlon] In Norwegian, the biathlon is called *skiskyting* (literally *ski shooting*).
[src:biathle/biathlon] In Norway, there are still separate contests in *skifeltskyting*, a cross-country race at 12 km with large-caliber rifle shooting at various targets with unknown range.
[src:biathle/biathlon] Called military patrol, the combination of skiing and shooting was contested at the Winter Olympic Games in 1924 and then demonstrated in 1928, 1936, and 1948, during which time Norway and Finland were strong competitors.
[src:biathle/biathlon] In 1948, the sport was reorganized under the Union Internationale de Pentathlon Moderne et Biathlon and became re-accepted as an Olympic sport in 1955, with widespread popularity within the Soviet and Swedish winter sport circuits.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The first Biathlon World Championship was held in 1958 in Austria, and in 1960 the sport was finally included in the Olympic Games.
[src:biathle/biathlon] At Albertville in 1992, women were first allowed in the Olympic biathlon.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The pursuit format was added for the 2002 Salt Lake City Winter Olympics, and the IBU added mixed relay as a format for the 2006 Olympics.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The competitions from 1958 to 1965 made use of high-power centrefire cartridges, such as the .30-06 Springfield and the 7.62×51mm NATO, before the .22 long rifle rimfire cartridge was standardized in 1978.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The ammunition was carried in several pouches on a belt worn around the competitor's waist.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The sole event was the men's 20 km individual, encompassing four separate ranges and firing distances of 100 m, 150 m, 200 m, and 250 m.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The target distance was reduced to 150 m with the addition of the relay in 1966.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The shooting range was further reduced to 50 m in 1978 with the mechanical self-indicating targets making their debut at the 1980 Winter Olympics in Lake Placid.
[src:biathle/biathlon] For the 2018–2019 season, fully electronic targets were approved as an alternative to paper targets used in zeroing or mechanical steel targets for IBU events.
[src:biathle/biathlon] In 1948, the International Modern Pentathlon Union (UIPM) was founded to standardize the rules for the modern pentathlon and from 1953 also biathlon.
[src:biathle/biathlon] In July 1993, the biathlon branch of the UIPMB created the International Biathlon Union (IBU), which officially separated from the UIPMB in 1998.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The following articles list major international biathlon events and medalists.
[src:biathle/biathlon] Unlike the Olympics and World Championships (BWCH), the World Cup (BWC) is an entire winter season of (mostly) weekly races, where the medalists are those with the highest sums of World Cup points at the end of the season.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The rules of the biathlon are given in the International Biathlon Union Competition Rules and the Annexes to the Event and Competition Rules which are updated by the IBU yearly.
[src:biathle/biathlon] A biathlon competition consists of a race in which contestants ski a series of loops on a cross-country trail system and includes either two or four shooting rounds called bouts, half in the prone position, the other half in the standing position.
[src:biathle/biathlon] Depending on the shooting performance, extra distance or time is added to the contestant's total skiing distance/time.
[src:biathle/biathlon] Depending on the event the contestant with the shortest total time or first to cross the finish line wins.
[src:biathle/biathlon] In order to keep track of the contestants' progress and relative standing throughout a race, split times (intermediate times) are taken at several points along the skiing track and upon finishing each shooting bout.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The large display screens commonly set up at biathlon arenas, as well as the information graphics shown as part of the TV picture, will typically list the split time of the fastest contestant at each intermediate point and the times and time differences to the closest runners-up.
[src:biathle/biathlon] At Olympic competitions, all cross-country skiing techniques are permitted in the biathlon, allowing the use of skate skiing, which is overwhelmingly the choice of competitors.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The minimum ski length is the height of the skier minus 4 cm.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The rifle has to be carried by the skier during the race by use of a harness and must be taken off during the shooting stages.
[src:biathle/biathlon] Competitors carry a rifle chambered in the 5.6 mm 22 long rifle caliber (.22 LR), which must weigh at least 3.5 kg (7.7 lb), excluding spare ammunition, and loaded or empty magazines.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The guns use .22 LR ammunition which must have a bullet with a weight of 2.55–2.75 grams (39.35–42.43 grains) made of lead or a similar uniform soft material and use a bolt action or Anschütz 1827F Fortner (or other straight-pull bolt) action.
[src:biathle/biathlon] Each rifle holds 4 magazines using a magazine cassette (holds all 4) or a magazine holder (holds one) mounted to the rifle or available internally, with 5 rounds each.
[src:biathle/biathlon] Additional rounds can be kept on the stock of the rifle for a relay race using what is called a spare round holder.
[src:biathle/biathlon] Spare rounds can also be stored on the floor plate of the magazine.
[src:biathle/biathlon] Spare round holders come in many configurations holding 2, 3, or 6 rounds of ammunition and are mounted in various places in the rifle stock depending on biathlete preferences.
[src:biathle/biathlon] Additionally spare round compartments are sometimes built into sight risers, cheek pieces or the standing grip of the rifle's stock.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The targets sit at a distance of 50 m (55 yd).
[src:biathle/biathlon] There are five concentric, circular, shooting targets to be hit in each shooting round or bout.
[src:biathle/biathlon] When shooting in the prone position, the target diameter is 45 mm (1.8 in); when shooting in the standing position, the target diameter is 115 mm (4.5 in).
[src:biathle/biathlon] This translates to angular target sizes of 0.9 and 2.3 mrad respectively.
[src:biathle/biathlon] A large assembly of 5 targets sits in each lane.
[src:biathle/biathlon] When changing from prone targets to standing, the hit size or scoring zone of the target changes, but the size of the bull at which the biathlete aims remains unaltered.
[src:biathle/biathlon] This means that the perceived target size remains the same while the "hit-zone" the biathlete's bullet must strike to achieve a hit decreases in the prone position when compared to the standing.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The setting of these targets is either done with a pull rope (as is done on mechanical targets) or by use of a wireless remote (as is done on electronic targets).
[src:biathle/biathlon] On biathlon ranges, a white paddle covers a hit target by using either the momentum of the bullet to flip a paddle or an acoustic system to determine the shot location.
[src:biathle/biathlon] This white indication method gives the biathlete, as well as the spectators, instant visual feedback for each shot fired.
[src:biathle/biathlon] Ear protection is not required or generally used during biathlon shooting as the ammunition used is usually subsonic.
[src:biathle/biathlon] An eyecup (blinder) is an optional feature of biathlon rifles.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The 20 km (12.43 mi) individual race [15 km (9.32 mi) for women] is the oldest biathlon event; the distance is skied over five laps.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The biathlete performs four bouts or shooting stages at any shooting lane (lanes 1–15 are in prone, while lanes 16–30 are for standing), in the order of prone, standing, prone, standing, totaling 20 targets.
[src:biathle/biathlon] For each missed target, a fixed penalty time, usually 1 minute, is added to the skiing time of the biathlete.
[src:biathle/biathlon] Competitors' starts are staggered, normally by 30 seconds.
[src:biathle/biathlon] A variation of the standard individual race, called short individual, was introduced during the 2018–19 Biathlon IBU Cup.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The races are 15 km for men and 12.5 km for women (the same distances as in the mass start), and for each missed target, 45 seconds will be added to the skiing time.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The sprint is 10 km (6.21 mi) for men and 7.5 km (4.66 mi) for women; the distance is skied over three laps.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The biathlete performs two bouts or shooting stages at a lane of their choosing, once in the prone position (usually lanes 1–15) and once in the standing position (lanes 16–30), for a total of 10 shots.
[src:biathle/biathlon] Most races designate these lanes for their positions in what is called a "split range".
[src:biathle/biathlon] The division of these lanes is marked with a pictorial sign showing an arrow and a representation of the designated position.
[src:biathle/biathlon] For each missed shot, a penalty loop of 150 m must be skied before continuing the race.
[src:biathle/biathlon] As in the individual competition, the biathletes start in a set of equal intervals as set by the race director.
[src:biathle/biathlon] Introduced at the 2017–18 Biathlon IBU Cup, the Super Sprint is a shorter version of the sprint race.
[src:biathle/biathlon] Unlike the traditional sprint race, the Super Sprint is divided into two segments – qualification and final.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The qualification is done like the traditional sprint, but on a 1.5 km lap with a total length of 4.5 km.
[src:biathle/biathlon] Only the top 30 competitors qualify for the final, in which all competitors start simultaneously and do five laps on the same course (like in mass start) with a total race length of 4 km.
[src:biathle/biathlon] During the final, the competitors have three spare rounds should they miss a target (like in relay race).
[src:biathle/biathlon] However, if not all targets are cleared during shooting instead of going on the penalty loop, the biathlete is disqualified from the race.
[src:biathle/biathlon] Changes were made for the following season with the course now being 1 km (0.2 km increase) meaning that the qualification race length will become 3 km, while the final race becomes 5 km in length.
[src:biathle/biathlon] Also the number of spare rounds was decreased from three to one.
[src:biathle/biathlon] In a pursuit, biathletes' starts are separated by their time differences from a previous race, most commonly a sprint.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The contestant crossing the finish line first is the winner.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The distance is 12.5 km for men and 10 km for women, skied over five laps; there are four shooting bouts (two prone, two standing, in that order) and each miss means a penalty loop of 150 m.
[src:biathle/biathlon] To prevent awkward or dangerous crowding of the skiing loops and overcapacity at the shooting range, World Cup Pursuits are held with only the 60 top-ranking biathletes after the preceding race.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The biathletes shoot on a first-come, first-served basis at the lane corresponding to the position they arrived for all shooting bouts.
[src:biathle/biathlon] If the pursuit follows an individual biathlon race, the lag behind the winner is halved.
[src:biathle/biathlon] In the mass start, racers start in a series of rows and columns as determined by their previous results.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The first racer to cross the finish line is declared winner.
[src:biathle/biathlon] As in sprint and pursuit, competitors must ski one 150 m penalty loop for each miss.
[src:biathle/biathlon] Here again, to avoid unwanted congestion, World Cup Mass starts are held with only the 30 top ranking athletes on the start line (half that of the Pursuit as here all contestants start simultaneously).
[src:biathle/biathlon] Starting in the 2018/2019 season, the Mass Start 60 became part of the International Biathlon Union (IBU) competition formats.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The Mass Start with 60 starters does not replace the current Mass Start with 30 starters.
[src:biathle/biathlon] All participants ski the first lap, but only the first 30 competitors perform a prone shooting bout, the next 30 consecutive contestants (designated by bib number) perform another lap on the course.
[src:biathle/biathlon] At the end of the second lap, the second groups performs their first shooting bout, and the first 30 perform another lap on the course.
[src:biathle/biathlon] After all biathletes have completed their first prone bout, the race progresses like a typical mass-start, all competitors complete their remaining prone bout, and two stages of standing shooting concurrently.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The relay teams consist of four biathletes, who each ski 7.5 km (men) or 6 km (women), each leg skied over three laps, with two shooting rounds; one prone, one standing.
[src:biathle/biathlon] For every round of five targets, there are eight rounds available.
[src:biathle/biathlon] However, the last three can only be single-loaded manually, into the chamber of the firearm, one at a time from spare round holders or from rounds deposited by the competitor into trays or onto the mat at the firing line.
[src:biathle/biathlon] If there are still remaining targets after 8 fired shots, one 150 m (490 ft) penalty loop must be taken for each missed target remaining.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The first-leg participants all start simultaneously, and as in cross-country skiing relays, every athlete of a team must touch the team's next-leg participant to perform a valid changeover.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The mixed relay is similar to the ordinary relay, but the teams are composed of two women and two men.
[src:biathle/biathlon] From its first instance at the world championships in 2005 until the end of the 2017 season, the first two legs were always run by the women, followed by the men on legs 3 and 4.
[src:biathle/biathlon] Since the 2018 season however, the race can be started by either the men or women.
[src:biathle/biathlon] Additionally, for most of the event's history, the women's legs have been 6 km (3.7 mi) and the men's legs 7.5 km (4.7 mi) as in ordinary relay competitions.
[src:biathle/biathlon] However, since the 2019 season the event has all four legs being either 6 km (3.7 mi) or 7.5 km (4.7 mi).
[src:biathle/biathlon] This event was added to the Olympics starting in 2014.
[src:biathle/biathlon] In 2015, the single mixed relay was introduced to the Biathlon World Cup by the IBU.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The event is run on a 1.5 km (0.93 mi) course with a 75 m (246 ft) penalty loop, and each team consists of a female and a male biathlete.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The race is divided into four legs, with the first three being 3 km (1.9 mi) or 2 laps and the final leg being 4.5 km (2.8 mi) or 3 laps, totalling 13.5 km (8.4 mi).
[src:biathle/biathlon] After each leg, the biathletes exchange so that each biathlete completes two legs.
[src:biathle/biathlon] Specific to this format, the exchange happens immediately after the last shooting of each leg without skiing an additional lap (as is usually the case).
[src:biathle/biathlon] The race can be started by either the female or male member of the relay, with the finishing member performing an extra lap.
[src:biathle/biathlon] This event was added to the world championships in 2019.
[src:biathle/biathlon] A team consists of four biathletes, but unlike the relay competition, all team members start at the same time.
[src:biathle/biathlon] Two athletes must shoot in the prone shooting round, the other two in the standing round.
[src:biathle/biathlon] In case of a miss, the two non-shooting biathletes must ski a penalty loop of 150 m (490 ft).
[src:biathle/biathlon] The skiers must enter the shooting area together and must also finish within 15 seconds of each other; otherwise, a time penalty of 1 minute is added to the total time.
[src:biathle/biathlon] Since 2004, this race format has been obsolete at the World Cup level.
[src:biathle/biathlon] World Cup races are streamed via the IBU website.
[src:biathle/biathlon] The IBU maintains biathlon records, rules, news, videos, and statistics for many years back, all of which are available at its web site.
[src:biathle/biathlon] Biathlon is generally considered to be a sport with a low risk of injuries or accidents, as is also the case with cross-country skiing.
[src:biathle/biathlon] While some injuries from firearms accidents were more common in the past, these led to higher safety standards.
[src:biathle/biathlon] Biathletes, as endurance athletes, have an elevated risk of eating disorders.
